    id: "drilling-protocol", name: "Implant Osteotomy Protocols", cat: "Protocol — Surgical Technique",
    design: "2) Progressive diameter drills per manufacturer sequence\n3) Final drill matched to implant diameter (or undersized for soft bone)\nPer Salomó-Coll 2021: bone density, drill diameter, and speed all influence heat but irrigation overrides all.\n\nUNDERSIZING FOR PRIMARY STABILITY:\n• Soft bone (Type III/IV): skip final drill → implant compresses trabecular bone\n• Dense bone (Type I/II): full sequence → avoid compression necrosis\n• Moderate: final drill 0.3–0.5mm smaller than implant diameter\n\nOSSEODENSIFICATION (Densah Burs):\nPer Inchingolo 2021 MA: significantly higher insertion torque and BIC vs conventional.\nPer Cassetta 2022: IT correlates with ISQ at insertion but does NOT predict secondary stability. IT >50 Ncm provides NO additional benefit and risks overcompression.\n\n• Delayed: 6–8 wk healing, any adequate insertion torque\n• Early: 3–6 wk, ISQ >60 or ≥25 N·cm\n• Immediate: ISQ >65–70 AND ≥35 N·cm MANDATORY", protocol: "DRILLING PROTOCOLS & PRIMARY STABILITY\n\nCONVENTIONAL SEQUENTIAL DRILLING:\n1) Pilot drill (2.0–2.2mm) at 800–1200 RPM with copious irrigation\nProtocol: pilot drill conventional → Densah burs in CCW at 800–1500 RPM → copious irrigation → light pumping motion.\nBest for: Type III/IV bone, immediate placement, ridge expansion, sinus floor elevation.\n\nISQ & TORQUE TARGETS:\nLOADING THRESHOLDS:", evidence: "⚠ HEAT THRESHOLD: Per Paeßens 2025: without irrigation ALL osteotomies exceeded 47°C regardless of speed. With irrigation at 200 RPM: NONE reached critical temperature. IRRIGATION IS THE SINGLE MOST IMPORTANT FACTOR.\nPer Kalra 2025 MA: significantly higher ISQ at baseline AND follow-up; higher crestal bone levels (p<0.05).\nPer Shilpi 2025 RCT: OD significantly higher ISQ immediately (p≤0.001); no difference at 4 mo — secondary stability equalizes.\nPer Razaghi 2025 MA (non-immediately loaded):\n• ISQ <60: 4.1% failure\n• ISQ 60–70: 0.4% failure\n• ISQ >70: 0.2% failure\nPer Norton 2017: implants with IT ≤20 Ncm (including 'spinners'): 96.6% survival at 1–10 yr IF left submerged for healing. Low torque ≠ failure if managed correctly.\n⚠ Per Ko 2021 RCT: immediate loading 69.4% vs delayed 100% — STRICT selection\n⚠ Per Hammoudeh 2025: immediate loading HR 30.94; diabetes/periodontitis = risk factors", notes: "DRILLING PROTOCOLS & PRIMARY STABILITY\n\nCONVENTIONAL SEQUENTIAL DRILLING:\n1) Pilot drill (2.0–2.2mm) at 800–1200 RPM with copious irrigation\n2) Progressive diameter drills per manufacturer sequence\n3) Final drill matched to implant diameter (or undersized for soft bone)\n⚠ HEAT THRESHOLD: Per Paeßens 2025: without irrigation ALL osteotomies exceeded 47°C regardless of speed. With irrigation at 200 RPM: NONE reached critical temperature. IRRIGATION IS THE SINGLE MOST IMPORTANT FACTOR.\nPer Salomó-Coll 2021: bone density, drill diameter, and speed all influence heat but irrigation overrides all.\n\nUNDERSIZING FOR PRIMARY STABILITY:\n• Soft bone (Type III/IV): skip final drill → implant compresses trabecular bone\n• Dense bone (Type I/II): full sequence → avoid compression necrosis\n• Moderate: final drill 0.3–0.5mm smaller than implant diameter\n\nOSSEODENSIFICATION (Densah Burs):\nPer Kalra 2025 MA: significantly higher ISQ at baseline AND follow-up; higher crestal bone levels (p<0.05).\nPer Shilpi 2025 RCT: OD significantly higher ISQ immediately (p≤0.001); no difference at 4 mo — secondary stability equalizes.\nPer Inchingolo 2021 MA: significantly higher insertion torque and BIC vs conventional.\nProtocol: pilot drill conventional → Densah burs in CCW at 800–1500 RPM → copious irrigation → light pumping motion.\nBest for: Type III/IV bone, immediate placement, ridge expansion, sinus floor elevation.\n\nISQ & TORQUE TARGETS:\nPer Razaghi 2025 MA (non-immediately loaded):\n• ISQ <60: 4.1% failure\n• ISQ 60–70: 0.4% failure\n• ISQ >70: 0.2% failure\nPer Norton 2017: implants with IT ≤20 Ncm (including 'spinners'): 96.6% survival at 1–10 yr IF left submerged for healing. Low torque ≠ failure if managed correctly.\nPer Cassetta 2022: IT correlates with ISQ at insertion but does NOT predict secondary stability. IT >50 Ncm provides NO additional benefit and risks overcompression.\n\nLOADING THRESHOLDS:\n• Delayed: 6–8 wk healing, any adequate insertion torque\n• Early: 3–6 wk, ISQ >60 or ≥25 N·cm\n• Immediate: ISQ >65–70 AND ≥35 N·cm MANDATORY\n⚠ Per Ko 2021 RCT: immediate loading 69.4% vs delayed 100% — STRICT selection\n⚠ Per Hammoudeh 2025: immediate loading HR 30.94; diabetes/periodontitis = risk factors",
