    id: "allonx-planning", name: "All-on-X Treatment Planning", cat: "Protocol — Full-Arch Rehabilitation",
    design: "✅ Adequate bone for 4–6 implants with ≥35 N·cm insertion torque\n✅ No uncontrolled diabetes, active periodontitis, or heavy smoking\n✅ Adequate interocclusal space for prosthesis\n✅ Realistic esthetic expectations", protocol: "IMMEDIATE vs DELAYED LOADING:\nHowever: for SINGLE ANTERIOR implants, Per Wittneben 2023: 99.2% 1-yr, 95.8% 5-yr — immediate loading acceptable with strict selection.\n\nPATIENT SELECTION — WHO IS A CANDIDATE:", evidence: "ALL-ON-X: EVIDENCE-BASED TREATMENT PLANNING\n\nSURVIVAL DATA:\nPer Yang 2023: All-on-4 — 99.38% implant survival, 100% prosthesis survival at 1–4 yr.\nPer Nobre 2025: 20–25 yr follow-up — 90% implant survival, 92% prosthesis survival.\n\nALL-ON-4 vs ALL-ON-6:\nPer Zhang 2023 (217 patients, 3–13 yr): no significant difference in survival, MBL, or complications in general.\nAll-on-6 preferred for: elderly patients, opposing natural dentition, smokers, bruxers, long cantilever situations, low bone density.\n\nTILTED vs AXIAL IMPLANTS:\nTilted posterior implants (30–45°) engage more cortical bone and increase AP spread — reduces cantilever length. Evidence shows equivalent survival to axial implants.\n\nCANTILEVER LIMITS:\nAnterior-posterior (AP) spread determines maximum cantilever. General rule: cantilever ≤1.5× AP spread for mandible; ≤1× AP spread for maxilla.\n\n⚠ Per Ko 2021 RCT: immediate loading 69.4% survival vs delayed 100%.\n⚠ Per Hammoudeh 2025: immediate loading HR 30.94 (p=0.001); 5-yr: IL 60% vs DL 99%.\n❌ WHO IS NOT:\n❌ Uncontrolled diabetes (HR significantly increased)\n❌ Active periodontitis (must be treated first)\n❌ Heavy bruxism without splint compliance\n❌ Insufficient bone for ≥35 N·cm stability\n\nZYGOMATIC IMPLANTS: when maxillary posterior bone is insufficient for standard implants. Requires specialized training — refer if not trained.", notes: "ALL-ON-X: EVIDENCE-BASED TREATMENT PLANNING\n\nSURVIVAL DATA:\nPer Yang 2023: All-on-4 — 99.38% implant survival, 100% prosthesis survival at 1–4 yr.\nPer Nobre 2025: 20–25 yr follow-up — 90% implant survival, 92% prosthesis survival.\n\nALL-ON-4 vs ALL-ON-6:\nPer Zhang 2023 (217 patients, 3–13 yr): no significant difference in survival, MBL, or complications in general.\nAll-on-6 preferred for: elderly patients, opposing natural dentition, smokers, bruxers, long cantilever situations, low bone density.\n\nTILTED vs AXIAL IMPLANTS:\nTilted posterior implants (30–45°) engage more cortical bone and increase AP spread — reduces cantilever length. Evidence shows equivalent survival to axial implants.\n\nCANTILEVER LIMITS:\nAnterior-posterior (AP) spread determines maximum cantilever. General rule: cantilever ≤1.5× AP spread for mandible; ≤1× AP spread for maxilla.\n\nIMMEDIATE vs DELAYED LOADING:\n⚠ Per Ko 2021 RCT: immediate loading 69.4% survival vs delayed 100%.\n⚠ Per Hammoudeh 2025: immediate loading HR 30.94 (p=0.001); 5-yr: IL 60% vs DL 99%.\nHowever: for SINGLE ANTERIOR implants, Per Wittneben 2023: 99.2% 1-yr, 95.8% 5-yr — immediate loading acceptable with strict selection.\n\nPATIENT SELECTION — WHO IS A CANDIDATE:\n✅ Adequate bone for 4–6 implants with ≥35 N·cm insertion torque\n✅ No uncontrolled diabetes, active periodontitis, or heavy smoking\n✅ Adequate interocclusal space for prosthesis\n✅ Realistic esthetic expectations\n\n❌ WHO IS NOT:\n❌ Uncontrolled diabetes (HR significantly increased)\n❌ Active periodontitis (must be treated first)\n❌ Heavy bruxism without splint compliance\n❌ Insufficient bone for ≥35 N·cm stability\n\nZYGOMATIC IMPLANTS: when maxillary posterior bone is insufficient for standard implants. Requires specialized training — refer if not trained.",
    refs: ["yang-2023-allon4-survival","nobre-2025-allon4-20yr","zhang-2023-allon4-vs-6","ko-2021-immediate-loading-rct","hammoudeh-2025-loading-risk","wittneben-2023-immediate-esthetic","cardaropoli-2025-consensus"]
